Abstract

Current brain–machine interfaces remain constrained by Biological–Artificial Coupling Instability, a multi-domain mismatch phenomenon manifesting as mechanical discontinuity, chronic immune activation, signal degradation, and decoding drift. This work formulates a theoretical framework for Bio-Integrative Neural Interfaces, shifting the design paradigm from discrete implantation toward dynamic, tissue-equivalent substrates that structurally, biochemically, and informationally co-evolve with neural parenchyma. We formalize Biological–Artificial Coupling Instability as a non-dimensionalized coupling drag functional $\mathcal{D}_c$ bounded by structural, energetic, informational, and dynamic mismatches, and derive stability conditions from the stochastic thermodynamics of learning, specifically bounding the non-adiabatic entropy production rate of the adaptive decoder. We prove a dual-adaptive stability condition via Finsler-Lyapunov metrics and mutual information synchronization, and define Interface Zero as the asymptotic limit in an explicitly constructed Hilbert space $\mathcal{H} = L^2(\Omega, w(\mathbf{x})d\mathbf{x})$ of admissible biohybrid configurations. The framework is anchored by verified empirical milestones: ultralow-modulus conductive hydrogels ($G' \approx 280$ Pa), energy-efficient continual-learning spiking neural networks with Banditron/AGREL algorithms achieving 99% reduction in multiply–accumulate operations, vasculature-mimetic electronic scaffold topological guidance, and the N=1 existence proof of 13-year cone electrode histology. We augment the theory with a continuum ordinary differential equation model of microglial polarization incorporating IL-4/IL-10 dynamics and mechanobiological feedback, neural manifold alignment conditions based on Wasserstein distance, a minimal in silico validation pathway for $\mathcal{D}_c(t)$ evolution under FDA Computational Modeling and Simulation guidance, and intersectional failure mode analysis via Sobol' sensitivity indices. This work establishes a mathematically rigorous, experimentally defensible, and regulatorily actionable pathway toward high-bandwidth, self-stabilizing brain–machine coupling without chronic foreign-body degradation.

