1. Introduction

Brain–machine interfaces have achieved remarkable short-term bandwidth through advances in microfabrication, high-density electrode arrays, and decoding algorithms. Yet chronic stability remains fundamentally limited by the persistent boundary between artificial hardware and living neural tissue. This boundary induces a foreign-body response, glial encapsulation, mechanical shear stress, and non-stationary neural dynamics that degrade signal fidelity over months to years.

Recent empirical trajectories—including the histological evidence of neurite integration in cone electrodes after 13 years (N=1 existence proof), micro-tissue engineered neural networks forming functional host synapses, vasculature-mimetic electronic scaffolds guiding endogenous neural migration, ultralow-modulus conductive hydrogels with shear modulus $G' \approx 280$ Pa, and continual-learning spiking neural networks adapting to neural drift with a 99% reduction in computational overhead—demonstrate that biological integration, not mechanical refinement alone, is the decisive factor for long-term stability.

This work proposes a theoretical unification of these trajectories under the Bio-Integrative Neural Interfaces paradigm. We formalize interface instability as a non-dimensionalized multi-domain coupling problem, derive stability conditions from the stochastic thermodynamics of learning and adaptive control theory, and define Interface Zero as a mathematically tractable asymptotic regime in an explicitly defined function space. The framework is intentionally theoretical, using verified empirical findings as boundary conditions, existence proofs, and constraint anchors for rigorous mathematical modeling.

