2. Formal Problem Definition: Biological–Artificial Coupling Instability

We define Biological–Artificial Coupling Instability as the dynamical degradation of brain–machine coupling arising from four orthogonal mismatch domains.

Definition 2.1 (Mismatch Domains).

· Structural Mismatch $\mathcal{M}_s$: Elastic modulus discontinuity, topological incompatibility, interfacial stress concentration.
· Energetic Mismatch $\mathcal{M}_e$: Differences in power delivery, ion–electron transduction efficiency, metabolic coupling.
· Informational Mismatch $\mathcal{M}_i$: Divergence between neural population manifolds and decoder latent spaces; drift in tuning curves and mutual information.
· Dynamic Mismatch $\mathcal{M}_d$: Timescale separation between biological plasticity $\tau_{\text{bio}}$ and artificial recalibration $\tau_{\text{art}}$.

2.1 Non-Dimensionalized Coupling Drag Functional

To resolve dimensional inconsistency, we define a non-dimensionalized coupling drag functional $\mathcal{D}_c: \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} \to [0,1]$:

\mathcal{D}_c(t) = \sum_{k \in \{s,e,i,d\}} \omega_k \cdot \tilde{\mathcal{M}}_k(t)

where $\omega_k > 0$ are dimensionless weighting coefficients satisfying $\sum_k \omega_k = 1$, and each $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}_k$ is a normalized mismatch term:

\begin{aligned}
\tilde{\mathcal{M}}_s &= \frac{|G'_{\text{implant}} - G'_{\text{brain}}|}{G'_{\text{brain}} + \epsilon_G} \in [0,1], \\
\tilde{\mathcal{M}}_e &= \frac{|\dot{Q}_{\text{implant}} - \dot{Q}_{\text{tissue}}|}{\dot{Q}_{\text{tissue}} + \epsilon_Q} \in [0,1], \\
\tilde{\mathcal{M}}_i &= 1 - \frac{\mathcal{I}(X;Y)}{\mathcal{I}_{\text{native}}} \in [0,1], \\
\tilde{\mathcal{M}}_d &= \frac{|\tau_{\text{bio}} - \tau_{\text{art}}|}{\max(\tau_{\text{bio}}, \tau_{\text{art}}) + \epsilon_\tau} \in [0,1].
\end{aligned}

Here $\epsilon_*$ are small regularization constants preventing division by zero, and $\mathcal{I}_{\text{native}}$ is the mutual information baseline in healthy neural tissue. $G'$ denotes the shear storage modulus; $\dot{Q}$ is the volumetric power density associated with interface operation; $\mathcal{I}(X;Y)$ is the mutual information between neural signals $X$ and recorded/decoded outputs $Y$.

2.2 Instability Theorem

Proposition 2.1 (Biological–Artificial Coupling Instability Theorem).
Let $\mathcal{D}_c^* \in (0,1)$ be a threshold determined by glial activation energy and decoding drift tolerance. If $\mathcal{D}_c(t) > \mathcal{D}_c^*$ for $t > T_0$, then

\frac{d}{dt}\mathcal{I}(X;Y) < 0

and interface stability is non-stationary.

Proof Sketch. The proof rests on three pillars. First, the data processing inequality guarantees that mutual information cannot increase under any noisy transduction channel. Second, the theory of dissipative structures links excess entropy production—quantified by the structural and energetic mismatches—to the destabilization of the system's stationary state. Third, chronic neuroinflammation models demonstrate a threshold glial activation level beyond which neuronal health and synaptic connectivity degrade. The full formal proof is provided in Section 7.3 after the stochastic thermodynamics framework is established, where the causal chain $\mathcal{M}_s \to \mathcal{M}_e \to \mathcal{M}_i$ is made explicit.

