8. Immune Dynamics: Continuum Model of Microglial Polarization

We replace the classical binary M1/M2 microglial classification with a continuum representation of the functional spectrum, driven by key cytokines and mechanical cues.

8.1 Governing Ordinary Differential Equations

Let $A(t) \in [0,1]$ denote the fraction of microglia in a pro-inflammatory, amoeboid state, and $R(t) \in [0,1]$ the fraction in a pro-repair, ramified state. The dynamics are:

\begin{aligned}
\frac{dA}{dt} &= \alpha_A \cdot \operatorname{Stress}\bigl(G'(t), [\text{MMP}]\bigr) \cdot (1 - A) - \beta_A \cdot u_{\text{IL4}}(t) \cdot A - \gamma_A \cdot u_{\text{IL10}}(t) \cdot A, \\
\frac{dR}{dt} &= \alpha_R \cdot u_{\text{IL4}}(t) \cdot A + \gamma_R \cdot u_{\text{IL10}}(t) \cdot A - \beta_R \cdot R \cdot \bigl(1 - \operatorname{Colonization}(t)\bigr), \\
\frac{d[\text{GFAP}]}{dt} &= k_{\text{ast}} \cdot A - k_{\text{res}} \cdot [\text{GFAP}].
\end{aligned}

Variable Definitions.

· $u_{\text{IL4}}(t)$: interleukin-4 release rate from scaffold. IL-4 is the primary driver of the initial shift toward a pro-repair phenotype.
· $u_{\text{IL10}}(t)$: interleukin-10 release rate, crucial for sustained anti-inflammatory maintenance.
· $\operatorname{Stress}(G'(t), [\text{MMP}]) = \sigma_0 \cdot \bigl(1 + \eta_G \cdot |G'(t) - G'_{\text{brain}}|\bigr) \cdot \bigl(1 + \eta_M \cdot [\text{MMP}]\bigr)$: mechanobiological feedback term coupling immune response to time-varying material properties and enzymatic activity.
· $\operatorname{Colonization}(t)$: neurite infiltration fraction from the scaffold model of Section 5.
· $[\text{GFAP}]$: glial fibrillary acidic protein concentration, a marker of astrocytic activation.

8.2 Control Objective

The scaffold's immunomodulatory design aims to drive the amoeboid fraction $A \to 0$ and the astrocytic activation marker $[\text{GFAP}] \to [\text{GFAP}]_{\text{native}}$, thereby ensuring that structural and energetic mismatches $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}_s$ and $\tilde{\mathcal{M}}_e$ remain below threshold. The control inputs $u_{\text{IL4}}(t)$ and $u_{\text{IL10}}(t)$ are realized via phosphatidylserine-functionalized particle release, creating a closed-loop feedback system where inflammation triggers its own resolution.

