9. Neural Manifold Alignment via Optimal Transport

Population neural activity lies on low-dimensional latent manifolds that drift over time due to learning, plasticity, and tissue remodeling. We formalize decoder co-evolution as optimal transport between probability measures on neural state space.

9.1 Wasserstein Distance Formulation

Let $\mu_{\text{bio}}(t)$ and $\mu_{\text{art}}(t)$ be probability measures on $\mathbb{R}^d$ representing the neural activity distribution and the decoder's latent distribution at time $t$, respectively. The alignment error is defined via the 2-Wasserstein distance:

\mathcal{E}_{\text{align}}(t) = W_2\bigl( \mu_{\text{bio}}(t), \mu_{\text{art}}(t) \bigr) = \left( \inf_{\gamma \in \Gamma(\mu_{\text{bio}}, \mu_{\text{art}})} \int_{\mathbb{R}^d \times \mathbb{R}^d} \|\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{y}\|^2 \, d\gamma(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{y}) \right)^{1/2},

where $\Gamma(\mu_{\text{bio}}, \mu_{\text{art}})$ is the set of all couplings with marginals $\mu_{\text{bio}}$ and $\mu_{\text{art}}$.

9.2 Manifold Tracking Proposition

Proposition 9.1 (Manifold Tracking via Optimal Transport).
Suppose the decoder updates its parameters according to

\dot{\theta}_{\text{art}} = -\nabla_{\theta} \mathcal{E}_{\text{align}}(t) + \text{regularization},

and the neural manifold drifts with bounded velocity in Wasserstein space: $\|\dot{\mu}_{\text{bio}}\|_{W_2} \le V_{\max}$. Then the alignment error satisfies

\mathcal{E}_{\text{align}}(t) \le \frac{V_{\max}}{\lambda} + \mathcal{O}(e^{-\lambda t})

for learning rate $\lambda > 0$.

Proof. The proof follows from standard tracking error bounds in adaptive control, generalized to the Wasserstein space using the Benamou–Brenier formulation of optimal transport. The gradient descent update on $\mathcal{E}_{\text{align}}$ provides exponential convergence to a ball of radius $V_{\max}/\lambda$ around the drifting target. The $\mathcal{O}(e^{-\lambda t})$ term captures the transient due to initial misalignment.

This formalism respects the probabilistic nature of neural activity and provides a geometrically principled alternative to Hausdorff distance for manifold alignment, directly connecting to the Fisher information tracking lemma.

