Appendix F: Verification of AGREL Efficiency for On-Chip Adaptation

This appendix formalizes the computational complexity claims for the Attention-Gated Reinforcement Learning (AGREL) algorithm and provides the mathematical justification for the 99% reduction in multiply–accumulate (MAC) operations.

F.1 Algorithmic Description

AGREL (Attention-Gated Reinforcement Learning) is a three-factor learning rule for spiking neural networks. The synaptic weight $w_{ij}$ from presynaptic neuron $i$ to postsynaptic neuron $j$ updates according to:

\Delta w_{ij} = \eta \cdot e_i(t) \cdot \delta_j(t) \cdot A(t),

where:

· $e_i(t)$ is the eligibility trace of synapse $ij$, typically an exponentially decaying memory of pre–post spike coincidences.
· $\delta_j(t)$ is the postsynaptic error signal, a global neuromodulatory factor broadcast to all synapses of neuron $j$.
· $A(t)$ is the attention-gating signal, which modulates learning based on behavioral relevance.

Crucially, $A(t)$ and $\delta_j(t)$ are scalar, globally broadcast signals, not per-synapse gradient computations.

F.2 Complexity Analysis

Consider a spiking neural network with $N$ neurons and $S$ synapses. Let $f$ be the average firing rate (spikes per neuron per second). In cortical tissue, $f \approx 0.01$–$1$ Hz during normal operation.

Backpropagation (BP) Complexity:

· Forward pass: $\mathcal{O}(S)$ operations per time step, but typically implemented as dense matrix multiplies: $\mathcal{O}(N^2)$.
· Backward pass: Requires computing gradients of the loss with respect to every weight. This involves a full backward traversal of the computational graph: $\mathcal{O}(S)$ operations per layer, with memory access proportional to $S$.
· Total MAC operations per training iteration: $\approx 2S + \text{gradient computation overhead} \approx 3S$.

AGREL Complexity:

· Forward pass: Sparse event-driven computation. Only neurons that spike perform computation. The expected number of operations per time step is $\mathcal{O}(f \cdot S)$.
· Learning update: The eligibility trace $e_i(t)$ is updated locally at each synapse only when either pre- or postsynaptic neuron spikes: $\mathcal{O}(f \cdot S)$. The global factor $\delta_j(t) \cdot A(t)$ is computed once per postsynaptic neuron: $\mathcal{O}(f \cdot N)$.
· No backward pass. No gradient storage.
· Total MAC operations per time step: $\approx 2 f \cdot S$.

F.3 Reduction Ratio

The ratio of AGREL operations to BP operations is:

R = \frac{2 f \cdot S}{3 S} = \frac{2}{3} f.

For typical cortical firing rates $f \approx 0.05$ (5% of neurons active at any time), $R \approx 0.033$, corresponding to a 96.7% reduction.

In the specific implementation cited in the main text (Zhou et al., 2025), additional optimizations including weight sparsity and event-driven processing yield a 99% reduction in MAC operations and a 98% reduction in memory access.

F.4 Formal Verification of Learning Efficiency

Theorem F.1 (Regret Bound for AGREL).
Under standard assumptions (convexity, bounded gradients), the AGREL update rule achieves a regret bound of $\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{T})$ with a constant factor that is $f$ times smaller than the corresponding factor for full gradient methods.

Proof Sketch.
The AGREL update is an instance of a bandit convex optimization algorithm. The sparse updates reduce the variance of the gradient estimator, which directly scales the regret bound by the sparsity factor $f$. The full proof follows from the analysis of the Banditron algorithm (Kakade et al., 2008) adapted to the spiking neural network setting.

F.5 Thermodynamic Implication

The reduction in MAC operations directly translates to a reduction in energy dissipation. Using the Landauer bound, each bit operation dissipates at least $k_B T \ln 2 \approx 3 \times 10^{-21}$ J. For a network with $10^6$ synapses operating at 1 kHz, BP would dissipate approximately $3 \times 10^6 \times 10^3 \times 3 \times 10^{-21} \approx 9$ nW (theoretical minimum; practical implementations are ~$10^6$ higher). AGREL reduces this by a factor of $100$, bringing the power budget within the thermal safety limits for chronic brain implantation ($< 1$ mW).

